summary.seg: This manuscript contains the Commentary on the first Alcibiades of Plato by Proclus. It was copied in the 17th century by five scribes, whose work alternates with one another. Given the script used, and the watermarks of the paper, the manuscript was probably produced in England. A note records that the text was copied from a manuscript owned by the Dutch scholar and manuscripts collector Isaac Vossius; M.R. James, in his catalogue, assumed that this manuscript was Oxford, Bodleian Library, Barocci 140 .

msItem.incipit: f. 1r Τῶν Πλατωνικῶν διαλόγων καί πάσης ὡς εἰπεῖν τῆς φιλοσόφου θεωρίας
msItem.explicit: f. 119v τὸ κακὸν, καὶ τὸ αἰσχρόν
msItem.note: After f. 76r there is a lacuna, common to the text tradition: προτείνων τὰ λήμματα· καὶ γὰρ οὐρανὸς συμφωνίας ( L.G. Westerink, Proclus Diadochus. Commentary on the first Alcibiades of Plato (Amsterdam, 1954), section 204 l. 13). The scribe evidenced it writing a note, λείπει ἐνταῦθα φύλλο, and leaving ff. 76v-77r blank
On f. 106r the scribe, after τοῦ δὲ τὸ καλόν ( Westerink (1954), section 295 l. 3), left the rest of the leaf and f. 106v blank, although there is not a lacuna in the text

support.material:
Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. left pastedown-[i] Pro Patria with countermark GR surmounted by a crown in a circle in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Heawood Pro Patria 3700 which is dated to 1747 (England).
ff. [ii]-[v] Two columns surmounted by grapes, with letters M L I ( 67 50 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Heawood Post or pillar 3523 (with different letters) which is dated to 1665 (London).
Horn on a cartouche ( 65 ca. 50 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to the type Heawood Horn 2779 which is dated in 1650.
ff. 33-39 Horn on a cartouche; with countermark P C ( 65 45 ), in the centre of the leaf, comparable to the type Heawood Horn 2666-2700 dated in the last quarter of the 17th c. (England).
Horn on a cartouche; with countermark L P I I P ( 70 45 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to the type Heawood Horn 2672 , which is dated in 1678.
Lily on a cartouche, surmounted by a crown, under it letters H G ( 90 50 ), in the centre of the leaf, comparable to the type Heawood Fleur-de-lis 1653 .
ff. 29-32 Coat of arms surmounted by a crown, not clearly visible

foliation.p: Foliation in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right from 1 to 119; 6 blank leaves at the beginning and 4 at the end of the manuscript are unnumbered: [i] + [ii]-[vi], 1-119, [vii]-[x]

collation.p: Due to tight sewing of the quires and to the absence of signatures, it was not possible to reconstruct the collation.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in good condition. The edges of the leaves are uneven. There are a few stains on the first and last leaves.

layoutDesc.layout: A single column of 28-38 lines. The layout is irregular, it changes with the scribes, but also within the portions written by a single scribe. On ff. 58r-106r, passim, the lines have been traced in pencil. On ff. 58r-62r there is a single lateral margin, on the left of the leaves; on ff. 62v-106r, 110r-119v there are two lateral margins; on ff. 107r-109v the the width of the layout almost correspond with the width of the leaf.

handNote.p: ff. 1r-57v Hand A: a minuscule script, upright, probably by a western European hand.
The text is written in brown ink
ff. 58r-88r, 98v l. 20-99r, 110r-119v Hand B: a minuscule script, upright, probably by a western European hand.
The text is written in brown ink; on ff. 59v-60v the ink is black.
ff. 89r-91v, 97r-98v l. 20, 103r-106r Hand C: a minuscule script, characterised by curls and flourishing tails, probably by a western European hand.
The text is written in brown ink.
ff. 92r-96v Hand D: a minuscule script, characterised by a somewhat 'rigid' aspect, probably by a western European hand.
The text is written in brown ink.

additions.p: On the left pastedown is written the shelfmark, O.10.10.

On f. [ii] recto are written the old shelfmark, O.4.14, a title Alcibiades cum Procli scholiis, and a note Ex Is. Vossii codice, specifying that the text was copied from a manuscript owned by Isaac Vossius.
On f. [vi] recto there is a note in Latin about the text.
In the left margin of f. 1r is written the old shelfmark, O.4.14, which has been erased with lines.
On f. [x] verso has been written three time the name Thomas Norse.

binding.p: Modern binding, paper cover over pasteboards; parchment on spine, where are pasted three paper labels with the shelfmark O.10.10. 330 207 26

origin.p: The manuscript was copied in the 17th century in England, from a manuscript owned by Isaac Vossius (1618-1689) Vossius, Isaac, 1618-1689 (see note on f. [ii] recto).

provenance.p: The manuscript was part of the collection of the antiquary Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744 .

history.acquisition:
It was donated by Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744
in 1738. In the upper margin of f. 1r is pasted the Trinity College bookplate.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws partly on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1902), vol. 3, p. 508.
